collections.name: Culture and Soul - By Harry Shelswell
collections.description:
During my 10 year solo expedition across the globe I visited the land of Vanuatu, home to only 327,000 people, and one of the last remaining places on earth where local tribes still live as they have for thousands of years. I was fortunate enough to spend some time with a tribe there, greeted by the chief and his family.

I captured a series of portraits displaying their raw beauty, power, authenticity and soul.

This series was captured over the course of 8 years across the vast and untouched landscape of New Zealand. After embarking on a 10 year solo expedition around the globe, I visited the mountains of New Zealand multiple times, hiking across the rugged landscape while writing poetry and capturing these images.

Some of the rawest beauty I have ever seen was nestled in this vastly untouched land. Connecting both my heart and soul to the ever changing dance of life.

collections.name: TRIUMPHANT TRUMPETS 12/26/2024
collections.description:
In the Book of Revelation, seven trumpets are sounded, one at a time, to cue apocalyptic events seen by John of Patmos (Revelation 1:9) in his vision (Revelation 1:1). The seven trumpets are sounded by seven angels and the events that follow are described in detail from Revelation Chapters 8 to 11.
In the Bible, trumpets are used to communicate instructions from God, to celebrate, and to signal war: 
Military purposes: Trumpets were used to direct the camp and declare that the people were going to war. 
Celebration: Trumpets were used to remind people of God's faithfulness. 
Prayer: The sound of a trumpet was like a prayer to God, reminding Him of His promise to help. 
Instructions from God: Trumpets were used to tell people what to do and how to respond. 
Call to repent: Trumpets sounded at the end times to call people to repent of their sins. 
Return of Jesus Christ: The "trumpet call of God" announces the return of Jesus Christ for those who have faith in Him.

collections.name: CreateArtX: Digital Renaissance

Within this dynamic ecosystem, Lord Leapington, the distinguished amphibian aristocrat, bridges the gap between London's traditional gardens and cutting-edge blockchain technology with his revolutionary PondPool mining operations. This unique collection captures the evolution of value from physical to digital, as market movements reshape towering cityscapes, neural pathways predict trading patterns, and innovative technologies emerge from the unexpected fusion of nature and computation, all while celebrating the cultural revolution of cryptocurrency and its community.
